===Verb===
{{en-verb|leaps|leaping|'''[[leaped]]''', '''[[leapt]]''', or archaically '''[[lept]]''' or '''[[lope]]'''|'''[[leaped]]''', '''[[leapt]]''', or archaically '''[[lopen]]'''}}

# {{intransitive}} To [[jump]] from one [[location]] to [[another]].
#* {{circa|1450}} anonymous, ''Merlin''
#*: It is grete nede a man to go bak to recouer the better his '''leep'''
#* '''1600''', anonymous, ''The wisdome of Doctor Dodypoll'', act 4
#*: I, I defie thee: wert not thou next him when he '''leapt''' into the Riuer?
#* '''1783''', [[w:Hugh Blair|Hugh Blair]], from the “Illiad” in ''Lectures on Rhetoric and Belles Lettres'', lecture 4, page 65
#*: Th’ infernal monarch rear’d his horrid head, '''Leapt''' from his throne, lest Neptune’s arm should lay His dark dominions open to the day.
#* '''1999''', Ai, ''Vice: New & Selected Poems'', page 78
#*: It is better to '''leap''' into the void.

====Usage notes====
The choice between {{term|leapt|lang=en}} and {{term|leaped|lang=en}} is mostly a matter of regional differences: {{term|leapt|lang=en}} is preferred in British English and {{term|leaped|lang=en}} in American English. According to research by John Algeo (''British or American English?'', Cambridge, 2006), {{term|leapt|lang=en}} is used 80% of the time in UK and 32% in the US.

